body:
With Chipmunk, one of my Flutter projects started to have stale code analysis. As soon as I change something in the source, its effects are normally picked up elsewhere (eg. adding an extra argument to a function, earlier call sites will start to show the now missing new argument). Probably related: Usages in other project files (Ctrl+B) doesn't work, either, it shows no usage anywhere for an element that clearly has many.

This doesn't happen in this project now. The project has the very same internal structure as others, practically identical layout, two modules in Project Structure, a main and an Android. Starting the compilation cures the analysis almost immediately, it's only the background analysis that probably stops with an error somewhere.

I know it's very slim for reproducibility but I can't just wrap up the whole project and send it for inspection. Other projects and those I create right now from scratch work all right. Caches were invalidated. Is there any other data, maybe a log somewhere, that I could consult and send?

===

Build: AI-212.5712.43.2112.8512546, 202204281627,

AI-212.5712.43.2112.8512546, JRE 11.0.12+7-b1504.28-7817840x64 JetBrains s.r.o, OS Windows 10(amd64) v10.0 , screens 1920.0x1200.0

AS: Chipmunk | 2021.2.1; Kotlin plugin: 212-1.6.21-release-334-AS5457.46; Android Gradle Plugin: (plugin information not found); Gradle: (gradle version information not found); Gradle JDK: version 11.0.12; NDK: from local.properties: (not specified), latest from SDK: 22.1.7171670; LLDB: LLDB 3.1 (revision: 3.1.4508709); CMake: from local.properties: (not specified), latest from SDK: 3.18.1-g262b901-dirty, from PATH: (not found)

Also, the log file can be found from `Help > Show Log in Explorer` (or something like that). Clear it of confidential info and attach it here, too, please.


Now we're talking... Definitely. The log is twice as long as with the correctly functioning project and has errors like _Project roots of XXX have changed_ and _y.flutter.intl.utils.FileUtils - Failed to validate project structure_. Which is _Flutter Intl_, but somehow I have the hunch that these could be related.

If I only knew how to fix the project. :-)

[idea.zip](https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/files/8702676/idea.zip)

I didn't see anything interesting in the log file. IntelliJ logs the stack trace whenever project roots change, so that's not useful to us. The message from Flutter Intl is probably not related to analysis. If you want to be sure, disable Flutter Intl, restart, and see if the problem persists.

If you're willing, let's try something else. In the settings page for the Flutter plugin there is an option to enable verbose logging. Enable that and try your experiment again, then attach the log file here. And just to confirm, the log file was from the project in which analysis is not updating correctly, right?

Yes, that project. Just opening it, waiting for the background operations to finish, then trying Ctrl+B on an identifier that is sure to be used in the project, the IDE says it's nowhere to be found. Then leaving AS.

Judging by the size, it isn't that much more verbose... :-)

[idea.zip](https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/files/8703778/idea.zip)

Thanks! The new log did not have any additional messages from the Flutter plugin.

Just to confirm, the Flutter SDK is set correctly in the Flutter settings page?

I don't know what could be causing analysis to stop updating. I can think of one more thing to try. Exit the IDE, then in a terminal emulator do `flutter pub clean` then `flutter pub upgrade`. You might try `flutter pub repair`, but honestly we're just guessing.

@bwilkerson Do you have any other ideas?

Clean and Upgrade are routine parts of the day-to-day operation, I do them all the time, so that doesn't help. There's no 'pub repair' currently in Flutter, actually. Yes, SDK and everything are set correctly, the project works flawlessly in every other respect, including the app being published in the Google Play Store. :-)

I would still keep asking about this root change because I opened half a dozen other projects now with the log and none of the others do anything similar. Even if it's supposed to be benign, what could be the cause? I have another bug reported that might well be related but before I start to give stupid suggestions there, I'd like to get more info, if possible.

`.iml` has no root folder specified explicitely. I tried to delete the `.idea` folder and have it recreated, no change. I compared all files inside `.idea` to another project and, apart from obvious differences between projects, everything seems to be as equal as possible. There's no real discernible difference between this project and others. Very strange.

Try `dart pub repair`. I thought all the pub options were supported by flutter but apparently not.

It seems odd that the *.iml file has nothing like `<sourceFolder url="file://$MODULE_DIR$/lib" isTestSource="false" />`. Try this:
 - In the Project tool window, select `lib`
 - Right click (or whatever you do to show the context menu), scroll down to `Mark directory as` and slide over to the sub-menu to choose `Sources Root`
 - Close and re-open the project
 - Now you should have the missing line in your *.iml file

I rather doubt that will change anything, because it didn't for me. My sample project was working just fine before and after.

The Dart plugin modifies roots, causing the stack trace. It has nothing to do with the Flutter plugin. Unless you have the experimental option to have Java and Kotlin indexed. Then we do add roots. Did you enable that? If so, does disabling it help?

Also, did you try disabling the Flutter Intl plugin?

.iml: a misunderstanding. It does have that line. I meant it didn't have any reference to a specific folder, just $MODULE_DIR$ everywhere. It doesn't have an absolute path like 'E:\Android\Projects\XXX' anywhere. Which is OK, I just wanted to say that it wasn't possible for the absolute path and the actual folder the project is in to be different. My bad.

`dart pub repair` doesn't exist, either. :-)

Yes, I did disable Intl, and a few others.

No, I don't have any such experimental feature, even if that sounds promising, I'd love to see that fully supported.

Roots: I only asked because the other projects I compare to, where I have no problems with the analysis, don't do the same in the log.

Thanks! Could you try doing `fluter downgrade` and see if the problem exists with Flutter 2.10?

Sorry about the `repair` noise. I thought there was an option to re-download everything in the pub cache. Perhaps it was removed, or I was dreaming ...

I don't need to downgrade, actually, I only upgraded a few days ago and I already had the problem before. :-) Actually, I could change the project to -dev temporarily, too. -- No, that wasn't the solution, either.

Yes, there was a command like this, I already pruned my old, accumulated packages once or twice but I no longer recall the command.

Apparently, the analysis eventually happens, only maybe after minutes. See this new log. I was typing the answer to you, left AS idling, and when I returned _and_ I made a PgDn-PgUp in the IDE, forcing a redraw, the red squiggly finally appeared.

Nothing else happened between 20:48 and 20:52 according to the log.

[idea.log](https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/files/8719472/idea.log)

`flutter pub cache clean` and `flutter pub cache repair`

I cleaned it now, I like nice clean caches without accumulated crud, anyway. :-) But it didn't help. Same as before, it happens eventually, just after minutes of apparently doing nothing.

Could you check your task manager for excess dart.exe jobs? If you have one project open in one Android Studio you should have one dart.exe, unless you are running a Flutter app, in which case you'd have two. That's assuming you are not using a Flutter tool from the `Tools > Flutter` menu. All those spawn Dart processes, but should all exit quickly.

If you do have more than you should, it is safe to kill them. The analysis server will be restarted automatically by Android Studio.

The experimental feature I mentioned can be enabled in the Flutter plugin settings page. It is toward the bottom, and mention Java and Kotlin.

Right away, but I have very fresh news and not the best ones. :-)

I made a backup and deleted the whole project. Then I started from scratch. Then I re-copied my source files and various project settings, Flutter and Gradle alike. And by the time I arrived at the same, functional, compiling project, the symptoms are the same again: code analysis after a minute or so. And my other two problems (.iml file keeps growing and Flutter Intl, discussed elsewhere, but more than likely related, are reborn).

Processes: if I start without any dart,exe, I get two. But when I exit AS, one remains running. I can reach three or four, there's no obvious rhyme or reason, and when I exit AS at least one remains running, sometimes two. No matter whether a load a "good" project or this "bad" one.

I'm not too familiar with Windows. Is there a way to get the full command that is running for those Dart processes? I'd like to know for both what arguments it was given, to determine where in the plugin it was created.

Thanks for trying to re-create the project. Too bad it didn't help.

"Project roots have changed" are present again, by the way.

Now that I'm out of AS, the process staying behind had this command line:

    "E:\Android\flutter\bin\cache\dart-sdk\bin\dart.exe"  --disable-dart-dev --packages="E:\Android\flutter\packages\flutter_tools\.packages"  "E:\Android\flutter\bin\cache\flutter_tools.snapshot" daemon 

Killed, and I restart AS the normal way, now I have these two:

    "E:\Android\flutter\bin\cache\dart-sdk\bin\dart.exe"  --disable-dart-dev --packages="E:\Android\flutter\packages\flutter_tools\.packages"  "E:\Android\flutter\bin\cache\flutter_tools.snapshot" daemon 
    E:\Android\flutter\bin\cache\dart-sdk\bin\dart.exe language-server --client-id=Android-Studio --client-version=AI-212.5712.43 --protocol=analyzer
I'll make the opposite tomorrow, I'll clone the project and start removing things to see if I spot something that makes a difference.

The plot always thickens. I made a clone, the usual way (duplicated the files, removed `.idea`, opened in AS, changed the Project window back to Project) -- and it works all right now!

Now comes the fun part. Cloning obviously means a different folder. In this case, I cloned `netprinter` to `netprinter_xxx`. So, as the next step, I moved the old one out of the way, renamed `_xxx` back to the old name, deleted `.idea`, opened again). And it still works. What kinda suggests that I could have solved the whole problem just by removing `.idea` in the first place, still, it isn't that simple as recreating everything from scratch restored the error, too.

So, I kept a copy of both "old" and "new" and will methodically compare them, this times the files in `.idea`, to see what I can see. (And yes, the old one keeps showing the problem if I copy it back to the original place and open it up again).

No discernible difference at all. I think the end result is that whatever it was, it _wasn't_ inside the project, none of its files or settings. Something in the stored, cached artifacts, settings or whatever. This kinda explains why my restarting from stratch didn't help -- it still used the same folders as earlier. But as soon as I started to open up a new folder, add new projects, remove old projects, I accidentally bumped something that triggered the change for the better.

The root change messages are gone, too. I can't help thinking that this had something to do with all the other problems. So, if any of you could have an idea of what actually triggers it...

It is possible that the Dart analyzer cache data became corrupt. If you really want to see if the original project can be restored, try deleting the cache. It is located at `C:\Users\<user_name>\AppData\Local\.dartServer` on Windows, and is `~/.dartServer` on Mac and Linux. Note that this cache is shared by all Dart projects, so everything will have to be re-analyzed.

I suppose this is exactly what _File > Invalidate Caches_ does, isn't it? At least what comes after it looks very much like it.

Anyway, with the reshuffling I described above, now everything is back to normal. So, probably, we'll never know for sure what caused it in the first place...

I close this now. Thanks for the effort. :-)

OK, glad you're back in good shape.

I added https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/issues/6190 to capture the thought of deleting the analyzer cache.
Also filed https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/issues/49096

title: Code analysis stale
